# Introduction
Strange weather is devastating the Bogataw River.  Can you navigate the flooded waters and deliver aid to the affected region?  Downpour is an adventure for 3 to 5 player characters starting at the 1st level with the adventure concluding at the 5th level.

The adventure takes place in the Bogataw Delta, a non-canonical area on the frontier of the forest wilderness.  The adventure has additional rules, so read the Running the Adventure section carefully.  The adventure is highly episodic, with players moving from one area to the next without being able to go back and with forked paths, making the story's progression somewhat predictable.  Because of this, it may not be necessary to review the adventure too far in advance.

## Adventure Background
The Bogataw Delta normally serves as a quiet path to the southern edge of the frontier, where adventurers, settlers, and missionaries all seek to claim the area from the natural forces that lurk there.  In the north, wild men move up the Snake River to explore the unknown forests beyond.  Further downstream, an oxbow formed in the river allows for farmers a try at a new life.  In the south, a tributary leads to a murky swamp, where the Buggarts and Gnomebillies find charm in all the things that drive others away from the area.

Rampant storms have started to flood the Bogataw Delta with increasing intensity causing devstation throughout the various settlements.  Among the threatened settlements is Gnome Grotto, home of Boss Bo, captain of the Loud Fairy and employer of the player characters.  Despite the perils of the storm and natural dangers along the river, Boss Bo seeks a crew to help him deliver aid supplies.

### The Myth of Chaspayu
The Bogataw Firbolgs tell the story of a great guardian spirit in the form of a snake named Chaspayu who protected the delta from those who would harm it.  Long ago, elves moved to the region and expand swiftly.  As they built their greatest city into what is now know as Snake Mountain, Chaspayu rose up against them, carving a path from the Bogataw River north towards the elves, destroying all in its path.  For their final stand, the elves had created magic weapons, known as the Beads of Binding.  As Chaspayu crashed down upon their city, the elves banished Chaspayu to another plane.  Although they had been wiped from the area, so too was the guardian spirit Chaspayu.  The Snake River is said to be the path Chaspayu carved, with Snake Lake the origin of his furious rampage. 
```
```
### The Bogataw Firbolgs
The Bogataw Firbolgs have inhabited the Bogataw Delta region as long as anyone can remember, so long that the area is named after their word for themselves.  They are generally peaceful, but are protective of their secrets, not speaking to outsiders, and guarding areas with awakened trees.  They are wary of the increasing expnasion of the outsiders, and fear Chaspayu's return.  The storms only reinforce their belief that the gods are angry with the settlers, and some believe the only way to save their homeland land is to drive away the outsiders.  

The Bogataw Firbolg Shamans wear wreaths of a local plant called Snakeberry, and greet each other in a ritual of respect where they bow then pick a berry from each other's wreaths.  Having grown on the river and with their large stature, the Bogataw Firbolgs are able to propel their canoes with great speed and dexterity.  Due to the other hostile inhabitants of the Bogataw Delta, the Firbolgs are also adept warriors and hunters, priding themselves most on their Giant Alligator and Dragon Turtle trophies.  To be accepted as an outsider by the Bogataw would take a feat brave enough to impress them.
<img src='https://media-waterdeep.cursecdn.com/attachments/thumbnails/4/188/250/256/c2-2.png' style='position:absolute;bottom:90px;right:-20px;width:450px' />
<div class='pageNumber'>2</div>
<div class='footnote'>Introduction</div>

\page
<img src='https://www.dandwiki.com/w/images/9/91/Bullywugs2.png' style='position:absolute;top:20px;right:30px;width:400px' />
### Reclaimed By Nature
The natural inhabitants of the Bogataw Delta seem to be the Bollywogs and Snapping Tortles which have fairly developed, if isolated societies.  They wish to drive all other races out of the Bogataw and claim it for themselves, and so they consistently perform raids on the surrounding communities.  

After the elves were driven out of the Bogataw Delta, Snapping Tortles moved into the ruins and quickly prospered, much to the jealousy of the Bollywogs.  With the flooding, the Tortles and Bollywogs couldn't be happier, hoping to aid the summoning of Chaspayu in any way they can, especially targetting Firbolgs and their allies.

In addition to the sentient life that occupies the Bogataw, particularly large creatures lurk in the area.  Reports of halflings drained completely dry by mosquitoes, alligators as large as boats, and toads being ridden as mounts circulate the various inns along the river.

### Rivergoer Life
Being at the forefront of the frontier, the Bogataw Delta is sparsely populated, with most of the towns existing to support the passing adventurers.  All sorts of races make it out to Bogataw for their various reasons, be it hunting, claiming new land, spreading the word of their god, or general trade, the Bogataw offers a wild life free from the large crowds one might encounter further up on Big River.

In addition to the general settlers, goblins, gnomes and gatormen have found a particularly cozy home in the southern swamp of the delta.  Goblins, known as Buggarts in the region, love a good hunt and cook out and are reckless to get it.  Using special machinery they race down the river in tiny boats, looting and hunting all the way.  Buggarts aren't inherently hostile, but they are opportunistic and will use violence if it seems like an easy choice.

Swamp gnomes, known as Gnomebillies, are quite similar to the Buggarts of the region, and the two tend to get along, especially since Gnomebilly tinkerers supply most of the hooch and guns for the Buggarts.  Unlike the Buggarts, Gnomebilly culture emphasize hospitality, so they tend to welcome outsiders rather than take advantage of them.

Gatormen feel right at home in the swampy water of the Bogataw Delta, leading them to be natural navigators.  Living in hidden shacks or mobile houseboats, gatormen mingle with the general population to make a quick buck as guides or pirates, whichever happens to take less energy at the time. 

### The Water Coven
The storms are no coincidence, but the work of three hags who are in the process of forming a coven.  They had learned about the Beads of Binding from a captured Bogataw shaman, and soon spread out to retrieve the powerful artifacts.  

At Snake Lake awaits the weakest of the hags, who guards the captured shaman and first Bead of Binding for her sisters.  At Green Lake, the second strongest hag unleashes evil upon the farmers in a rage that the first hag has stolen one of her Beads of Binding.  Finally, the strongest of the hags resides in the coven's base, holding the final Bead of Binding.  

As they see the power of the storms increasing, the more confident the power of their coven, eventually leading the three to reconcile and discover the true power of the beads.
```
```
<div style='margin-top:300px'>
  
### Elements In Flux
The disturbance of the Beads of Binding has caused the natural spirits to awaken to the new intrusion upon the wilderness.  Elementals run amok, mindlessly attacking all that get in their way.  In addition to the awakening of the elementals, the magic that manipulates them appears to be affected as well, with reports of casters spells fizzling out, or being extra powerful.

## Running the Adventure
This adventure assumes races and classes from the 5th edition book are being used, but should work for any homebrew additions given they are appropriately balanced.  Because the story revolves around a rushing river and Boss Bo's desire to get to Gnome Grotto, the adventure follows a fairly linear path, with few opportunities to go back to areas missed.  The synopsis below outlines the flow of the story.

#### Leveling Up
Rather than tracking experience points, players will advance at certain points in the story.  Level advancement will be noted at the point of the chapter it occurs.
### Adventure Synopsis
The player characters start in the camp of Sleepy Snake, having arrived there through a caravan of pioneers who cleared the mountains in the east.  The player characters are gathered at a log cabin inn seeking shelter from the storms outside when Boss BO approaches them and explains his situation.  As Boss Bo is the only way out of the camp due to the weather, the players should accept his quest for whatever reason they need.  After exploring Sleepy Snake, the players will board the Loud Fairy and head south towards the Fangs of the Snake.  After clearing the Fangs of the Snake, the player characters are faced with a fork in the river, where they must choose between the Mud Valley or Belly of the Snake.  Either choice leads to the town of Snake Bottom.
</div>
<div class='pageNumber'>3</div>
<div class='footnote'>Introduction</div>

\page

From here players have the choice to visit the location of Snake Lake and confront the Lake Hag there.  From Snake Bottom, the characters enter the Floodwaters.  From here, players arrive at Oxbow Port.  From Oxbow Port, chracters can visit Oxbow Farms and the Green Lake, or continue on down the Bogataw River or the Tribal Tributary if they know its secret location.  

Continuing on the Bogataw River leads to the village of Swampwater.  The Tribal Tributary ends in the Bogataw Village. 
Swampwater leads directly to the Boggart Bayou, and from the Boggart Bayou and Bogataw Village, the characters have the ability to travel back and forth as well as to The Boss' Pad, which leads to Hole of Horrors where the final hag resides.  From The Boss' Pad or Bogataw Village, players can proceed to Gnome Grotto.  Finally the players will confront Chaspayu himself where he rises anew.

### The Loud Fairy
The Loud Fairy is the ultimate creation of the Tinkerer Boss Bo, a giant paddle wheel boat powered by captured steam elementals.  The boat requires a pilot as well as the engine lever to stay in the on position.  

The paddle wheel is a dangerous construct and any creature knocked into it suffers 8d8 bludgeoning damage and is knocked off the ship.  

The ship itself is quite sturdy, and barring extraordinary circumstances can survive most beatings the river has to offer.
### Aid Supplies
Boss Bo's journey relies on delivering enough aid supplies to Gnome Grotto to help.  He will refuse to advance if there are not enough aid supplies, represented in **supply points**, and will require the players loan him money so he can purchase more at 5 gp per **supply point**

Although the Loud Fairy itself can take a beating, it is still a rickety ship, and supplies tend to get thrown overboard.  Players should be careful when navigating otherwise the journey can get rather expensive!
### The Coming Storm
Boss Bo is in a hurry to deliver aid before the next storm hits, but there's only so much time to sail in the flooded waters.  Certain events have a **time point** listed with them.  At certain parts of the chapters, it will be noted that attempted and completed events with **time points** should have their number tallied, then certain effects occur depending on the number of points accrued.
>The number of **time points** does not reset.  Dungeon Masters should track this number throughout the campaign to appropriately assign consequences.
