# Chapter 1: Snake River
Snake River flows from the unexplored west, and meets the Bogataw River in the south at Snake Bottom.  Normally only nimble explorers who can navigate the deadly rapids known as the Fangs of the Snake travel upriver, but recently a caravan company has discovered a pass through the mountains, bringing new waves of pioneers to the normally quiet camp of Sleepy Snake, which lies just beyond the Fangs.  The player characters have come in the latest wave, but have heard that they cannot continue forward, as the flooding wiped out the caravan as the attempted to continue upriver and the cannot go back due to mudslides. 

The adventure starts with all the players gathered before Boss Bo at the Sleepy Snake Inn, a quickly assembled log cabin with a single long table, a small iron stove behind a counter, and several cots in the back.


Boss Bo begins the adventure by giving a monologue detailed below.


**Caravan Payment.**  Pioneers spend their life savings to get a spot in the caravans going west.  Player characters start with 50 gp less than normal, even if bankrupts them.

## Snake Bottom
Snake Bottom is a small camp northwest of the Fangs of the Snake.  A few vendors have set up permanent locations, but otherwise the population is transient.  Apart from the buildings alongside the riverside, the forest dominates the landscape.  Hidden amongst the trees is an ancient wood elf shrine who can be found by following the path of a local plant called Snakeberries.  Apart from a few canoes and a kayak, a paddelwheel barge sits alongside the rickety wooden pier.
### Snake Bottom Inn
The Snake Bottom Inn is a large, longhouse-style cabin.  On one side are a series of small cots, on the other a long wooden table where all the guests sit.  In the corner is wooden counter with a small iron stove behind it.  Next to the stove are various crates and barrels filled with grog and various foodstuffs.  The rain is getting bad enough that water drips from certain parts of the ceiling, making the straw floor smell damp.

#### Boss Bo
Boss Bo (NG Gnomebilly) kicks off the adventure with a monologue about hit home of Gnome Grotto, a tiny village built in the murky depths of the Bogataw Swamp.  As captain of the Loud Fairy, he's traveled up and down all regions of the Bogataw Delta many a time, and with his "patented paddlewheel technology (patent pending)", he can usually move upstream, making him a cherished resource for those in the Sleepy Snake camp.  He's fairly good-spirited due to his moonshine intake, but quick to anger.  Boss Bo appears to only wear a straw hat and overalls, yet he manages to carry many a useful item on his person.
```
```
**Treasure.**  Boss Bo loves to tinker and is constantly working on a new invention.  At certain points in the story, if there are enough aid supplies and few enough time points, Boss Bo has been able to concentrate long enough to finish a new invention to give away.  The reward will be noted in that part of the chapter.

**Develoment.**  Boss Bo greets the adventurers with the following at the start:

<div class='descriptive'>
Howdy ya'll.  I'm mighty sorry all yer friends got swept away in the river, but we warned them!  The storm's ain't to be reckoned with.  It's flooding everyone out.  Never seen weather like it!  Some say it's dark magic, but whatever's going on, I gotta get home to help out.  Just heard my whole village is underwater.  Seeing as I'm the only way out of this mud hole, I thought I'd offer you a job as crewmen aboard my state of the art boat!  As soon as you can, load up the supplies from Baermor's and come get me.  Remember, time is of the essence!
</div>
Accepting Boss Bo's offer is non-optional.
#### Tasha
Tasha (NG Halfling) is a stout woman with an unwelcoming look on her face.  She's quite worried her cellar is being flooded and wishes to go check, but she also has to finish off the soup.  Immediately after the players finish talking to Boss Bo, Tasha calls out to the player characters for aid.  She hands them a recipe card supposedly received from a "strange halfling boy, obsessed with the quality of the soup."

**Treasure.**  The recipe's text doesn't seem to be written in any mortal language.  Passing a DC 15 Wisdom check allows the players to make sense of the maddening glyphs.  Otherwise, any player with proficiency with cook's utensils can finsih the soup off with their own falir without consulting the recipe.  When returning to speak with Boss Bo, Tasha rewards each player with Snake Soup, an item that restores 1d4+2 hit points when consumed.  The successful cook also gets 2 gp.

#### Bazoo and Janya
Bazoo (NG Human) and Janya (CG Half-Orc) both sit covered in furs, bursting out in laughter.  You can overhear the following conversation as Bazoo hands Janya a piece of gold:
<div class='descriptive'>
Bazoo:  Haha, that was good!  Another!
   
___
Janya:  What did the fish say when it ran into a wall? ...Dam!
Bazoo (laughing):  Too funny!  A little something for you!
</div>
**Treasure.**  If the player characters can tell Bazoo a joke involving the word "fish", he will look through his pockets only to find his Lucky Penny.
<div class='pageNumber'>5</div>
<div class='footnote'>Chapter 1</div>
\page

> #### Bazoo's Lucky Penny
> *Wondrous item, uncommon*
> 
> This copper piece seems to glisten despite having been on a dirty trapper's person for so long.  Bazoo claims it's imbued with good luck, and if the situation is right, the bearer may find themselves getting out of dangerous situations by the skin of their teeth like he has all these year.
>
> This penny has 3 charges.  A charge can be expended to flip the coin as a bonus action.  The player must guess heads or tails.  If their guess is the result of the coin flip (or die if no coin is handy), they receive a +2 to their next attack roll or saving throw.  The penny regains 1d3  expended charges per short rest.
#### Aezalith
Sitting far away from the two raucous trappers is a researcher (LG High Elf) hoping to document the ways of the Bogataw Firbolgs and discover more about the wood elf civilization that used to exist along the Snake River.  

**Development.**  Aezalith is happy to share her knowledge with anyone who will listen.  She reveals the following to the players:
* Snakeberry is considered a holy omen amongst the Bogataw Firbolg and tends to grow around areas of great importance.

* There is a wood elf shrine near the Snake Bottom camp that she's searching for.

* Bogataw shaman wear wreaths of snakeberry in their hair.

* Bogataw Firbolg tend to avoid speaking Common and Elvish on their own indisputed territory, speaking Bogataw Giant preferrably or Bogataw Sign Language to outsiders.

* She teaches the Bogataw sign for "friend."

#### Aradiah and Emmabelle
Two pioneers (LG Halflings) who also stayed behind from the doomed caravan, mostly due to lack of finances.  They sit looking forlorn waiting to hear more news of their companions that went ahead.

**Development.**  Aradiah and Emmabelle warn of scammers along the river who board ships to help fight off enemies, then pirate the vessels they've just saved.

<img 
  src='https://i.imgur.com/d3y1xtk.png' 
   style='width:325px; margin-left:-30px; margin-top: 30px; border-radius: 50%'/>
```
```


### Bait Shack
One of the few permanent structures among the Sleepy Snake camp, the shop appears more as a pile of boards rather than an actual building, but somehow it stays watertight.  The door flaps open and closed in the stormy winds.

#### Tagadaw Steve
Inside the bait shack is a man (NG Human) wearing an outfit similar to Boss Bo's.  He's occupied gathering a bunch of nets and javelins from the various barrels scattered around the shack when you come in.  Due to the noise from the flapping door, he's completely unaware from the players'entrance.
#### Skeeter Swatting
**Treausre.**  Tagadaw Steve was preparing to take out 2 **Giant Mosquitos** buzzing around his shack out back.  If the players offer to clear the monsters from his shack, then he provides them with two nets, 10 javelins, and a vial of acid.  If the players defeat the **Giant Mosquitoes**, Tagadaw Steve awards the players two jars of his special bait.  This adds **1 time point**.  

He also tells you the following joke.
<div class='descriptive' style='margin-bottom: 50px'>
Why did the fisherman cross the road?  Just for the halibut!
</div>

> #### Tagadaw Steve's Bait
> *Wondrous item, uncommon*
>
> This jar is filled with an oily substance that stinks of every kind of animal excrement one can imagine.  Despite its gross nature, fishermen down the river are always eager to get their hands on it due to its effectiveness.
>
> The jar contains enough bait for 3 uses.  
Players can use an action to smear the bait on anything within 5 ft. or throw a ball of it as an improvised weapon.  River creatures within a 30-foot radius must pass a DC 15 Wisdom saving throw or be compelled to head directly towards the bait and consume it if able.  While under the effect of the bait, creatures have disadvantage on saving throws, and attacks against it have advantage.

#### Inventory
Tagadaw Steve has the following items for sell:

| Item | Cost |
|:----:|:-------------|
| Acid (vial) | 20 gp |
| Javelin | 1 gp |
| Bucket | 1 sp |
| Net | 1 gp |
| Pro Fishing Tackle | 3 gp |
| Steve's Bait (jar) | 30 gp |
| Rope, hempen (50 feet) | 1 gp |

<div class='pageNumber'>6</div>
<div class='footnote'>Chapter 1</div>
 \page
### Frontier Supplies Shop
At the edge of the port lies the last permanent structure of the Sleepy Snake campsite.  This cabin-like structure is much better built than the other two and even has a sign with bright yellow lettering which reads "Frontier Supplies."
#### Baermor
Inside the Frontier Supplies shop, an older man (LG Dwarf) is occupied marking a clipboard with counts of crates stacked before him.  As the players enter, he simply glances to the side as he keeps counting.
<div class='descriptive'>
...sixty-two nets, eighty-nine rolls of bandages, two-hundred-odd rations, hundred-and-four candles, ninety-two tindersboxes...Oh a Frontier Supplies hello to you.  Unfortunately I am completely out of stock, but if you'd like to place an order...
</div>

Baermor isn't just helping Boss Bo out of friendship.  His son Falfor was on a trade mission in the swamp when the last storm hit and he has not heard word of him since.  He is desperate to find any news he can about him and has tasked Boss Bo with finding out information and bringing it back.

#### Swampy Cellar
Once the players establish thy're working for Boss Bo, Baermor directs them to load the rest of the crates in the flooded cellar below.  He warns he's heard a mean croaking, and has been too scared to go by himself lest he be eaten whole.  A series of rickety steps behind the counter leads to a small opening below the floorboards of the main shop where water sits up to the ankle.  Almost no light enters the cellar, just enough to make out several crates scattered around the cellar.

---
**Treasure.**  Hiding in the corner is a **Giant Frog**.  After dispatching of the beast, the adventurers can begin to load the crates onto the boat by passing a collective DC 60 Strength check.  Failing the check causes one of the adventurers to drop their crate, revealing a suit of **Animated Armor** which attacks the players unless soothed by music; this adds **1 time point**.  If the armor is destroyed, it drops its helmet.  If the armor is soothed, it will follow the musician, who can use an action to play a song and make the armor take an action.  Once the crates are delivered or the armor is taken care of, Baermor gives each player 1 sp.  

#### Inventory
Baemor has packed away everything worth selling into the various crates.

### Snakeberry Shrine
Hidden amongst the trees, this shrine is impossible to find except for the Bogataw Shaman and the most well-versed ethnologists.  The only clue to its location is a patch of bushes covered in Snakeberries at the far edge of the Sleepy Snake camp.  The shrine was abandoned long ago, containing lost secrets of the old Wood Elf civilization that lived there before.
#### Snakeberry Trail
By following one Snakeberry patch to the next, the adventurers can find the shrine.  To notice the patch in the first place, the players must have talked to Aezalith about the shrine or pass a DC 18 Nature check or DC 21 Perception check.  Once the patch is discovered, a further DC 11 Nature check or DC 14 Perception check will reveal the whole trail.  If any adventurer attempts to pick the berries once on the trail, the bushes reveal themselves to be **Awakened Shrubs** and at least 6 will attack. Following the trail takes **1 time point**, fighting the angered forest takes **2 time points**.
#### Shrine Carvings
At the end of the trail lies a giant stone covered in swirls of different pictographs.  Two trees stand to either side of it, perfectly straight, as if engineered.  If the adventurers navigated the trail without angering the forest, they hear a deep chanting from the other side of the stone, otherwise a Firbolg stands in front of the stone with a line drawn at his feet and weapons drawn.
#### Agakwah
The Firbolg at the shrine is a shaman known as Agakwah.  He is on a mission to discover the truth of the intense weather plaguing the region and heard that the Snake River held the story of Chaspayu and how the Wood Elves defeated the spirit long ago.  If the adventurers attack Agakwah, the two trees next to the shrine come to life as **Awakened Trees** and Agakwah retreats into the forest.  If the adventurerss befriend Agakwah, he translates the story on the ruins, teaches the players the sign for "have story", and gives them a shamanic blessing, granting advantage on the next saving throw the players have to take.

### Leaving Sleepy Snake
After the adventurers have finished their work in the twon, they must return to Boss Bo to confirm all the supplies are packed.  The adventurers will board the Loud Fairy with Boss Bo at the wheel, and set off.  The players can pretty much occupy an area on the boat they please, but they must stay on the boat, as the Loud Fairy is moving too fast, and the waters are too turbulent for any swimmer to keep up naturally.
#### Blinding Ambush
A loud croaking can be heard around the Loud Fairy.  If the adventurers can pass a DC 15 Perception check, the relative location of the croaks can be found, allowing the adventurers to repositions before 3 **Giant Frogs** board the ship.  While the adventurers are distracted a sneaky tortle has made its way onto the Loud Fairy and is sneaking up to attack Boss Bo.  A DC 18 Percetion check reveals the tortle, and upon his defeat he smashes a bottle filled with a green smoke that blinds Boss Bo and anyone else within a 15-foot radius if they fail a DC 11 Constitution saving throw.  Because Boss Bo cannot see, he asks the crew to temporarily appoint a new pilot until the poison wears off.  The adventurers must choose someone to sit at the wheel for the next part of the journey.
